issue.title: Homepage FAQ Section – Insufficient Padding and Spacing
issue.body: Description: The FAQ section on the homepage currently lacks adequate padding and spacing between question items and surrounding elements. This results in a visually cluttered layout that affects readability and user experience. Steps to Reproduce: Navigate to the homepage. Scroll to the FAQ section. Observe the tight spacing between FAQ items and lack of vertical padding. Expected Behavior: Each FAQ item should have: Sufficient vertical spacing between questions. Padding within each item for better readability. Consistent margins aligning with the overall page layout. Suggested Fix: Add padding-block and margin-block to FAQ items. Consider using utility classes like py-4, mb-2, or space-y-4 (if using Tailwind). Ensure responsive spacing across breakpoints. Screenshot: Hi I'd like to take up this issue and ensure the FAQ section meets accessibility and visual clarity standards. As an active contributor in GirlScript Summer of Code 2025, I’ve been consistently working on optimizing UI components, resolving layout inconsistencies, and improving CSS hierarchy across the project. I specialize in responsive design using Tailwind and semantic HTML, and I’ve previously addressed similar spacing and alignment issues in the gallery and footer sections. I'll refactor the FAQ layout to include proper padding, spacing, and responsive behavior, ensuring it aligns with the overall design system. Assigning this to myself now — looking forward to delivering a clean and accessible fix! Assignee: @janavipandole

Fixes #1.

Summary of changes:

- Uses Qt 6.8 (minimum) to provide a graphical frontend.
  - Graphical version cannot be distributed as a single binary because of shared library requirements. It will need to be distributed as a zip/tarball/deb/rpm/installer etc. CPack should make this easy.

- Added a few extra data members to DTOs for better presentation.
- Some classes (Options and Layout are the big ones) gained setters where they previously had none.
- Reworked solver output around callbacks instead of outputting directly.
- Lifted big chunks of README.md into the UI with light editing to suit context.

Thoughts?

issue.title: Quantification using the identification results obtained from pGlyco
issue.body: 1.After I finished downloading the software, I noticed that its interface was somewhat different from that described in the user manual. Could you please tell me what the function of iRT Calibration is? (Checking the "iRT Calibration" option seems to cause a crash.) 2. If I use the identification results from pGlyco for quantification, which identification result from the pGlyco report should I input?

comment.body:
1. The user manual was written for the old version of GlyPep-Quant, which is the original version. The corresponding software with old GUI is provided in the [GlyPep-Quant repository](https://github.com/DICP-1809/GlyPep-Quant/releases). The iRT function is developed for retention time calibration with standard iRT peptides identification. This function is only for glycopeptide samples with iRT peptide addition. Please do NOT choose this box for common glycopeptide samples.
2. "pGlycoDB-GP-FDR-Pro-Quant-Site.txt" is the final identification result of pGlyco3. Please choose this file.
Essential columns in pGlyco3 results for GlyPep-Quant reading are: RawName, Scan, Charge, PrecursorMZ, Peptide, Mod, GlycanComposition, Glycan(H,N,A,F), PlausibleStruct, GlySite, TotalFDR
For MS1 spectrum data reading, please place the corresponding mass spectrum file (.mzML or . raw file) under the same directory as pGlyco3 result.

pull_request.title: feat: Add ConnectionDefinition support to registration utilities
pull_request.body:
This PR adds support for ConnectionDefinition entities in the MeshKit registration system. Previously, when importing models that contained connection definitions, these entities were being silently ignored because the registration pipeline didn't know how to handle them.

## What was broken

The main issue was in `utils/utils.go` - the `FindEntityType` function was missing a case for `connections.meshery.io`, so it couldn't identify connection definition files. This meant connection definitions were being skipped during model import.

## What I fixed

- Added the missing `connections.meshery.io` case to `FindEntityType` in `utils/utils.go`
- Made `getEntity` public as `GetEntity` in `models/registration/utils.go` so it can be tested
- Updated `PackagingUnit` in `models/registration/register.go` to include connections and handle their registration
- Added connection file processing in `models/registration/dir.go` 
- Added connection support to the database schema in `models/meshmodel/registry/registry.go`
- Created the `ConnectionDefinition` type in `models/meshmodel/core/v1beta1/connection.go`
- Added `ConnectionSchemaVersion` constant in the corev1beta1 package

Based on reviewer feedback, I've made the following adjustments:
- Reverted `GetEntity` back to unexported `getEntity` since it's not used outside the package
- Moved `ConnectionSchemaVersion` constant to the corev1beta1 package
- Removed unnecessary changes to OPA and OCI files that were unrelated to the ConnectionDefinition task
- Kept only the essential changes needed for ConnectionDefinition support

## Testing

I tested this with a sample ConnectionDefinition JSON file. The pipeline now works correctly:
- `FindEntityType` properly identifies connection definition files
- `getEntity` parses them into the right type
- The registration process handles them end-to-end

Before this fix, connection definitions were just being ignored. Now the registry can properly handle all entity types: components, relationships, and connections.

Related to #762

---

**Notes for Reviewers**
- [Signed commits](CONTRIBUTING.md)
- [x] Yes, I signed my commits.

- Created the `ConnectionDefinition` type in `models/meshmodel/core/v1beta1/connection.go`
- Added `ConnectionSchemaVersion` constant in the corev1beta1 package

Based on reviewer feedback, I've made the following adjustments:
- Reverted `GetEntity` back to unexported `getEntity` since it's not used outside the package
- Moved `ConnectionSchemaVersion` constant to the corev1beta1 package
- Removed unnecessary changes to OPA and OCI files that were unrelated to the ConnectionDefinition task
- Kept only the essential changes needed for ConnectionDefinition support

## Testing

I tested this with a sample ConnectionDefinition JSON file. The pipeline now works correctly:
- `FindEntityType` properly identifies connection definition files
- `getEntity` parses them into the right type
- The registration process handles them end-to-end

Before this fix, connection definitions were just being ignored. Now the registry can properly handle all entity types: components, relationships, and connections.

Related to #762

issue.title: Critical: Trigram index panics on Unicode content during string slicing
issue.body:
## 🐛 Bug Report

### Description
The trigram index crashes with a panic when processing Unicode content due to unsafe string slicing at byte boundaries that don't respect UTF-8 character boundaries.

### Error Details
```
thread 'main' panicked at src/trigram_index.rs:653:46:
byte index 497 is not a char boundary; it is inside '中' (bytes 496..499)
```

### Location
File: `src/trigram_index.rs:653`
Code: `format!("{} ...", &content_str[..497])`

### Root Cause
The code attempts to slice a string at a fixed byte position (497) for creating a content preview, but this position may fall in the middle of a multi-byte UTF-8 character. When the content contains Unicode characters like Chinese text '中', the slice operation panics.

### Impact
- **Severity**: CRITICAL - Causes complete application crash
- **Affected Operations**: 
  - Git repository ingestion fails
  - Any document insertion with Unicode content fails
  - Database becomes unusable for international content

### Reproduction Steps
1. Create a document with Unicode content (Chinese, emoji, etc.)
2. Try to insert it into KotaDB
3. Application panics at trigram index insertion

### Discovery Method
Found during dogfooding validation while ingesting KotaDB's own codebase, which contains Unicode test files (`tests/unicode_handling_test.rs`).

### Suggested Fix
Use proper UTF-8 aware string slicing:
```rust
// Instead of:
format!("{} ...", &content_str[..497])

// Use char_indices to find safe boundary:
let truncate_at = content_str.char_indices()
    .take(497)  // Take first 497 chars
    .last()
    .map(|(i, _)| i)
    .unwrap_or(content_str.len());
format!("{} ...", &content_str[..truncate_at])
```

### Related
- `tests/unicode_handling_test.rs` - Contains Unicode test cases that trigger this bug
- Issue #106 mentioned in the test file about Unicode handling

### Priority
This is a **CRITICAL** bug that completely breaks Unicode support and makes KotaDB unusable for international content.

### Validation Note
This issue was discovered through continuous dogfooding validation (Issue #214), demonstrating the value of testing KotaDB on its own codebase.

comment.body:
## Additional Context from Dogfooding

This bug was discovered during continuous dogfooding validation (Issue #214) while attempting to ingest the KotaDB codebase into itself for testing.

### How It Was Found
- Ran `cargo run -- -d data/analysis ingest-repo .` to ingest KotaDB's own codebase
- The process crashed immediately when it encountered the Unicode test file `tests/unicode_handling_test.rs`
- The crash occurred during trigram index insertion for documents containing multi-byte UTF-8 characters

### Impact Analysis
- **Complete System Failure**: Any document with Unicode characters crashes the entire database
- **Data Loss Risk**: Ingestion processes fail partway through, potentially leaving the database in an inconsistent state  
- **International Support Blocked**: Makes KotaDB completely unusable for non-ASCII content
- **Test Files Affected**: Even having Unicode test files in a repository prevents ingestion

### Related Issues
- Discovered as part of continuous dogfooding effort (#214)
- Related to Issue #106 mentioned in the Unicode test file

### Verification
Reproducible 100% of the time with any Unicode content including:
- Chinese characters (中文)
- Emoji (🚀)
- Accented characters (café)
- Any multi-byte UTF-8 sequences

### Suggested Testing After Fix
1. Run full repository ingestion with Unicode test files
2. Test with international content (Chinese, Japanese, Arabic, etc.)
3. Ensure trigram generation works correctly across character boundaries
4. Verify content preview truncation respects UTF-8 boundaries throughout the codebase

This critical bug prevents dogfooding validation and makes KotaDB unusable for any real-world content containing Unicode characters.

issue.title: Move layer opacity one level up in the project file
issue.body:
### Use case

Currently, opacity is at `layers[{layerId}].parameters.opacity`. `layers[{layerId}].parameters.*` contains fields that are specific to the layer type, specified in `packages/schema/src/schema/project/layers`. Every schema in that directory contains a `opacity` property. `layers[{layerId}].*` contains fields that are generic to all layers, like `visible`. Those are defined in `packages/schema/src/schema/project/jgis.json`.

### Preferred solution

I think `opacity` is the exact same type of property as `visible` -- it's generic to all layers, and their actual functions are in the same category. I think they should be siblings, `layer[{layerId}].opacity`, `layer[{layerId}].visible`. They would both be defined only once in `packages/schema/src/schema/project/jgis.json`.

### Alternative solutions

_No response_

issue.title: BlockDispenseLootEvent should include the LootTable that was run

type.name: Feature
type.description: A new feature for the product that has yet to be developed, or an improvement to an existing feature or task.

issue.body:
### Is your feature request related to a problem?

There is currently no way to get the loot table key that was run during the BlockDispenseLootEvent, the best you can do is look up the TrialSpawner configuration and filter by ominous/normal to get a list of weighted LootTables, which is not useful when wanting to check which loot table was run to replace it with other items. 

### Describe the solution you'd like.

I would like the LootTable used to initially generate the items in the BlockDispenseLootEvent to be exposed as a getLootTable in the event. Both places this event is called from (TrialSpawners and Vaults) currently have the NMS-equivalent LootTable readily available.

### Describe alternatives you've considered.

Getting the trial spawner configurations and filtering based on the Map of weighted LootTables, but this isn't useful when wanting to check the exact loot table that was randomly picked to drop the items. 

### Other
